content:
If a dashboard is running slowly, it's likely because of inefficient source reports or many people refreshing it at once. To speed up sluggish dashboards, optimize source report performance by creating fast-running source reports and filtering data efficiently.

Create source reports that run fast: The best way to speed up a slow dashboard is to speed up its source reports. Filter report data efficiently, remove unnecessary columns, hide detail rows, and write efficient formulas.

Base your dashboard on as few source reports as possible: Ideally, base your dashboard on a single source report. Each widget gets its data from one source report, so having fewer source reports means faster refreshing dashboards.

Subscribe to a dashboard instead of having lots of people refresh it at the same time: Subscribe to a dashboard and set a schedule for when you want it refreshed. Salesforce will cache the data and send the results to recipients by email. This way, viewers don't need to refresh the dashboard again.

Combine multiple widgets into one: Sometimes, two or more widgets can show the same data in one widget, which means fewer source reports run, and the dashboard refreshes more quickly.

Split a dashboard in two if it's taking too long to refresh: If you have a dashboard with many widgets that takes a long time to refresh, consider splitting the dashboard into two separate dashboards. This way, each dashboard will load faster.

To link from one dashboard to another, edit a widget by clicking on it and enter the URL of the destination dashboard in the "Edit Component" menu.
title: Optimizing Salesforce Dashboards for Faster Refreshes
